TUBERCULOSIS TRANSMISSION RISK IN AIDS PATIENTS (3)
===================================================

[This posting collects two additional replies on this subject]
.................................................
[1]
From: brnbaum@unixg.ubc.ca (David Birnbaum)
Date: Sat, 23 Mar 1996 23:33:56 -0800 (PST)
Thoughts that come to mind with your case include three possibilities:
1. missed lesion on chest film (AIDS and pulmonary collapse being
noteworthy), in which case there may have been risk of aerosol transmission
if the patient had been coughing or receiving aerosol therapy;
2. primary infection, in which case there is minimal transmission risk in
hospital but public health may want to investigate a community source;
3. miliary tuberculosis, in which case there is a risk of transmission to
either laboratory staff who might have been exposed via aerosolized urine
during test procedures, or to autopsy staff;
all assuming, of course, that the organism isn't an atypical mycobacterial
species and that there is no reason to suspect pseudoinfection (false
positive culture results have been documented in the literature).
I assume that the CDC Guideline you refer to is MMWR 1994;43(RR-13).
--
David Birnbaum, PhD, MPH
University Of British Columbia (Canada)
e-mail: brnbaum@unixg.ubc.ca
