[2]
From: Drbob6@aol.com
Date: Sat, 23 Mar 1996 22:27:02 -0500
Addressing the assessment of risk for transmission of TB in an HIV + patient:
You may wish to revise your guidelines in light of the fact that
the CXR [chest X-ray] of an HIV + individual with TB disease may
often not only not appear unusual but may even appear entirely
normal (see Core Curriculum on Tuberculosis, 3rd edition, 1994).
My personal approach in this matter is to use the following criteria
for determining potential risk of pulmonary TB in an HIV + patient:
History of persistent cough (>2 weeks) plus ANY TWO of the
following symptoms - fever, anorexia, hemoptysis, weight loss,
night sweats. I include neither PPD [tuberculin skin test] nor
CXR interpretation as criteria in such instances. Subsequently, any
patient meeting these criteria is assumed to be infectious until
TB has been ruled out. Hope this helps.
--
Drbob6@aol.com
